> What if you change "--config Debug" to "--config Release" or "--config RelWithDebInfo". Does the issue still exist? (I don't expect ONNX Runtime python Windows Debug build would work well.)

No, this is explicitly a bug only in the debug configuration as the title and description of the bug both indicate. This is also a *recent* issue - we've had no problems with Debug Windows builds previously. Adding the `/bigobj` flag is the default for projects such as `llvm-project` and `onnx-mlir` specifically to support Debug builds on Windows - it should be a fairly minor change to `onnxruntime` to add the flag.

issue.title: Add /bigobj for MSVC builds

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
Currently, the Windows Debug build of onnxruntime fails with "fatal error C1128: number of sections exceeded object file format limit: compile with /bigobj".

This change adds `/bigobj` to the build flags for MSVC in order to increase the limit.

This addresses https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/9396

repository.name: onnxruntime

issue.body:
**Description**: 

1. Make ORT training and inference CPU pipelines share the same template file. It will also allows us easily adding Prefast to training CI pipeline. Currently it is turned off because there are some warnings needed be fixed.
2. The template file ORT training windows CI pipelines used was wrong. The file was designed for building nuget packages so it doesn't build python part. So ORT training python code was not tested. However, most training users use python. This PR will fix the cpu part. Later on I will have a similar PR to re-work the GPU part.
3. Move training Win CPU CI pipeline to inference Win CPU CI pipeline. Move training Win GPU CI pipeline to inference Win GPU CI pipeline. To reduce the pipelines we need to manually queue. And, it still gives you the flexibility run them individually.  
4. Workaround #9396. This is not a fix. It's a workaround. A real fix requires refactoring the C/C++ code. 


**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
